## 💻 Step 4: Coding Exercise Hardening & Toolchain Mechanics

### 🏗️ File Infrastructure & Setup

To test manual package building and path resolution from a clean terminal workspace, classes were arranged across isolated conceptual directories:

```text
workspace/
├── Config.java         <- Returns system greeting string
├── Application.java    <- Contains main entry point method
├── AppTester.java     <- Formulates built-in verification logic
└── bin/                <- Dedicated destination target for compiled bytecode

```

### 🛠️ Terminal Execution Steps (Compilation & Decoupling)

#### 1. Compile with Destination Management

We use the `-d` (destination) compiler flag to compile our dependencies and redirect the artifact directly into our destination folder without generating messy workspace clutter:

```bash
javac -d bin/ Config.java Application.java AppTester.java

```

#### 2. Verify Automation via the Native Assertion Engine

Java bypasses assertion execution by default to ensure optimized production runtime cycles. To turn our code into a primitive test runner, we must pass the explicit **Enable Assertions flag (`-ea`)** along with our explicit classpath definition:

```bash
# Unix-based Systems (Linux/macOS)
java -ea -cp bin:. AppTester

# Windows CMD / PowerShell
java -ea -cp "bin;." AppTester

```

If a conditional check inside our test script fails, the JVM intercepts the instruction and drops a clean, localized `AssertionError` directly to standard output.

