## 🚀 Step 5: Engineering Insight — Compile-Time vs. Runtime

| Characteristic | Compile-Time Dependencies (`javac`) | Runtime Dependencies (`java`) |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Enforcer** | The Java Compiler. | The JVM Dynamic ClassLoader. |
| **Objective** | Verifies type safety, valid method definitions, syntactic accuracy, and strict contract matches. | Locates, links, and loads explicit bytecode blocks dynamically into heap memory for immediate execution. |
| **Artifact** | Raw `.java` source code paths and structural library headers. | Compiled `.class` files bundled into structural paths or JAR binaries on the active Classpath. |

### Architectural Importance

This strict division allows us to compile code against static interface contracts while choosing or altering the implementation bytecode completely on the fly at runtime. This structural mechanic is what enables frameworks like Spring to execute Dependency Injection and tools like JUnit to load tests without compile-time knowledge of our classes.

